==English==
===Etymology===
From [[Middle English]] "me thinketh" (‘seems to me’) < Old English "me thyncth". In [[Early Modern English]], used at least 150 times by William Shakespeare; in [[Middle English]] by writer Geoffrey Chaucer, "me thinketh"; and in [[Old English]] by ''Alfred the Great'', "me thincth."

===Verb===
'''methinks'''

# {{archaic}} It [[seem]]s to me.

====Examples====
William Shakespeare:
:methinks the truth should live from age to age,
:—King Richard III: III, i 

Geoffrey Chaucer:
:Me thinketh accordant to reason
:To telle you al the condicion

Alfred the Great:
:Forthy me thincth betre,
:gif iow swæ thincth,
:thæt we eac sumæ bec

